===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `cat` baraye namayesh mohtaviate yek file rooye safe namayesh (terminal) estefade mishavad. Hamchenin mitavanad file-ha ra be ham chasband va natije ra dar yek file jadid zakhire konad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `cat filename`  --> 📜 Namayesh mohtaviate file.
    🔹 `cat file1 file2`  --> 👀 Namayesh mohtaviate file1 va file2 be tartib.
    🔹 `cat > filename`  --> ➕ Ijad yek file jadid va gereftane voroodi az karbar ta zamani ke Ctrl+D زده شود.
    🔹 `cat file1 >> file2` --> 📏 Ezafe kardane mohtaviate file1 be entehaaye file2.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ cat example.txt

    🔹 Namayesh mohtaviate file "example.txt".

    $ cat file1.txt file2.txt

    🔹 Namayesh mohtaviate file1.txt va file2.txt dar edameye ham.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ cat > newfile.txt
    Hello, World!
    (Ctrl+D)

    $ cat newfile.txt
    Hello, World!

    🔹 Ijad yek file ba name "newfile.txt" va neveshtane "Hello, World!" dar aan. Dastoor `cat newfile.txt` mohtava ra namayesh midahad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `cat` command displays the contents of a file on the terminal. It can also concatenate multiple files and redirect the output to a new file.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `cat filename`  --> 📜 Display the contents of the file.
    🔹 `cat file1 file2`  --> 👀 Display the contents of file1 and file2 sequentially.
    🔹 `cat > filename`  --> ➕ Create a new file and take input from the user until Ctrl+D is pressed.
    🔹 `cat file1 >> file2` --> 📏 Append the contents of file1 to the end of file2.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ cat example.txt

    🔹 Display the contents of the file "example.txt".

    $ cat file1.txt file2.txt

    🔹 Display the contents of file1.txt and file2.txt concatenated together.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ cat > newfile.txt
    Hello, World!
    (Ctrl+D)

    $ cat newfile.txt
    Hello, World!

    🔹 Creates a file named "newfile.txt" and writes "Hello, World!" to it. The `cat newfile.txt` command then displays the contents.